content.problemStatement:
The **post-decrement operator (x--)** in C is used to reduce the value of a variable by 1, but only after its current value has been used in an expression. It is especially useful in scenarios like loops, countdowns, or when processing an item before reducing a counter or index.

**Syntax:**
```c
variable--;  // Equivalent to: variable = variable - 1;
```
---
**Example:**
```c
#include

int main() {
    int count = 13;  // Initialize count with 13

    // Print the value before any operation
    printf("Before decrement: %d\n", count);

    // Post-decrement: print current value, then decrement
    printf("Using count--: %d\n", count--);

    // Print the value after decrement
    printf("After decrement: %d\n", count);

    return 0;
}
```

**Expected output:**
```c
Before decrement: 13
Using count--: 13
After decrement: 12
```

